04697nam a22007095i 9780231549806DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021058012  a97802315498067 a10.7312/chrz192442doi  a(DE-B1597)635311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGT2855b.C47 2022 4aGT2855 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a394.1/2223/eng/202207261 aChrzan, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnxious Eaters :bWhy We Fall for Fad Diets /cKima Cargill, Janet Chrzan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArts and Traditions of the Table: Perspectives on Culinary History00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter One WHY WE LOVE FAD DIETS -- tChapter Two FOOD REMOVAL DIETS -- tChapter Three FOOD ADDICTION -- tChapter Four CLEAN EATING -- tChapter Five PALEO DIETS -- tChapter Six FINAL THOUGHTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat makes fad diets so appealing to so many people? How did there get to be so many different ones, often with eerily similar prescriptions? Why do people cycle on and off diets, perpetually searching for that one simple trick that will solve everything? And how did these fads become so central to conversations about food and nutrition?Anxious Eaters shows that fad diets are popular because they fulfill crucial social and psychological needs—which is also why they tend to fail. Janet Chrzan and Kima Cargill bring together anthropology, psychology, and nutrition to explore what these programs promise yet rarely fulfill for dieters. They demonstrate how fad diets help people cope with widespread anxieties and offer tantalizing glimpses of attainable self-transformation. Chrzan and Cargill emphasize the social contexts of diets, arguing that beliefs about nutrition are deeply rooted in pervasive cultural narratives. Although people choose to adopt new eating habits for individual reasons, broader forces shape why fad diets seem to make sense.Considering dietary beliefs and practices in terms of culture, nutrition, and individual psychological needs, Anxious Eaters refrains from moralizing or promoting a “right” way to eat. Instead, it offers new ways of understanding the popularity of a wide range of eating trends, including the Atkins Diet and other low- or no-carb diets; beliefs that ingredients like wheat products and sugars are toxic, allergenic, or addictive; food avoidance and “Clean Eating” practices; and paleo or primal diets. Anxious Eaters sheds new light on why people adopt such diets and why these diets remain so attractive even though they often fail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aDietxSocial aspects. 0aFood habitsxSocial aspects. 0aNutritionxSocial aspects. 0aReducing dietsxPsychological aspects. 0aReducing dietsxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aCargill, Kima, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chrz1924440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231549806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231549806/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK